VALUES
  ('castillo-de-san-marcos', 'Castillo de San Marcos', 'St. Augustine', '1 South Castillo Drive', 'FL', 29.8978, -81.3114, 'other', 'The oldest masonry fort in the continental United States, built between 1672-1695 from native coquina stone. This massive Spanish fortress has witnessed over 350 years of warfare, siege, imprisonment, and death under five different national flags.', 'The Lady in Blue, believed to be Maria Mancilla searching for her soldier husband, haunts the grounds in a flowing blue gown. In 1784, Colonel Marti murdered his wife Dolores and Captain Abela after smelling her perfume on his uniform - their bodies were sealed in a wall. Visitors smell her perfume in the dungeon, feel phantom touches, and become nauseous. Spanish soldiers still patrol the battlements centuries after their deaths.', 1695, 'https://ghostcitytours.com/st-augustine/haunted-places/castillo-de-san-marcos/'),

  ('st-augustine-lighthouse', 'St. Augustine Lighthouse', 'St. Augustine', '81 Lighthouse Avenue', 'FL', 29.8858, -81.2886, 'lighthouse', 'A 165-foot lighthouse with 219 steps, built in 1874 to replace a crumbling Spanish watchtower. USA Today readers voted it one of the top 10 best haunted destinations in the United States. Featured on Ghost Hunters, CNN, and the Weather Channel.', 'Two young girls, Eliza and Mary Pittee, drowned in 1873 when a supply cart rolled into the water during construction. Their playful spirits are seen in period dresses, giggling and running up the tower stairs. A former lighthouse keeper walks the grounds at night. Visitors capture orbs, hear children laughing, and feel cold spots in the keeper''s house where the girls once lived.', 1874, 'https://www.visitstaugustine.com/things-to-do/ghost-tours'),

  ('huguenot-cemetery', 'Huguenot Cemetery', 'St. Augustine', '34 San Marco Avenue', 'FL', 29.8976, -81.3085, 'cemetery', 'Established in 1821 as the city''s Protestant burial ground, containing at least 436 bodies including victims of devastating yellow fever epidemics. Mass graves hold up to 25 bodies stacked vertically, with only the top name marked on the stone.', 'Judge John Stickney roams the cemetery after drunk men stole his gold teeth during exhumation. A 14-year-old girl in a wispy white dress appears near midnight - she died during a yellow fever outbreak and was buried in a pauper''s tomb when no one claimed her body. During yellow fever anniversary dates in August and September, phantom funeral processions dissolve into mist when approached.', 1821, 'https://ghostcitytours.com/st-augustine/haunted-places/huguenot-cemetery/'),

  ('old-jail-st-augustine', 'Old Jail', 'St. Augustine', '167 San Marco Avenue', 'FL', 29.8990, -81.3107, 'prison', 'Built in 1891 by Henry Flagler to serve as the city''s prison for nearly 60 years. The building housed hardened criminals alongside the sheriff and his family, who lived under the same roof across from the prisoners they watched.', 'Inmates were treated inhumanely, with many physically tortured and executed at the gallows. Visitors hear painful moaning, chains rattling, and the heavy footsteps of Sheriff Perry, known for his harsh punishment practices. The sound of a little girl coming from the sheriff''s quarters sends frightened guests fleeing the premises. Prisoners who lost their lives within these walls never left.', 1891, 'https://staugustineghosttours.com/the-spirits-of-the-old-jail-museum/'),

  ('spanish-military-hospital', 'Spanish Military Hospital', 'St. Augustine', '3 Aviles Street', 'FL', 29.8930, -81.3128, 'hospital', 'A museum dedicated to medical practices during St. Augustine''s Second Spanish Period from 1784-1821. Originally a convalescent home transformed into a military hospital in 1791, replacing a palm-thatched hospital described as a "miserable hole."', 'Thousands of human bones were discovered beneath the hospital during 1821 construction. The "Mourning Ward," where priests gave Last Rites to dying patients, echoes with cries and distant conversations. A phantom imprint appears on one of the beds, creaking as if someone is laying on it. In the surgical room where crude amputations occurred, visitors hear faint sounds of surgical instruments and muffled cries.', 1791, 'https://staugustineghosttours.com/the-haunts-of-the-spanish-hospital/'),

  ('casa-monica-hotel', 'Casa Monica Resort & Spa', 'St. Augustine', '95 Cordova Street', 'FL', 29.8916, -81.3134, 'hotel', 'Built in 1888 by architect Franklin W. Smith and purchased by Henry Flagler four months after opening. The lavish Moorish-Spanish style hotel was voted in the 2024 Top 25 Historic Hotels of America Most Haunted Hotels.', 'A guest hanged himself from the ceiling in room 511, and now visitors feel icy winds, cold spots, and hear footsteps when alone. The Flagler Suite contains a mysterious child''s handprint on the bathroom mirror that cannot be removed. A housekeeper knocked on the suite door and heard "We''ve been expecting you" - but found the room empty. A gentleman in 1920s clothing walks throughout the hotel.', 1888, 'https://www.hauntedrooms.com/florida/haunted-places/haunted-hotels/casa-monica-hotel-st-augustine'),

  ('flagler-college', 'Flagler College', 'St. Augustine', '74 King Street', 'FL', 29.8908, -81.3122, 'university', 'Originally the luxurious Hotel Ponce de Leon, built by Henry Flagler in 1888 and designed by Thomas Hastings and John Carrere. The Spanish Renaissance-style building is now a private college named after its founder.', 'Henry Flagler himself haunts the college where his grand hotel once stood. His second wife Ida, who was committed to an asylum after claiming to communicate with a Ouija board, also roams the halls. The Woman in Black, believed to be Flagler''s mistress, appears to students. Strange noises, shadow figures, and an unexplained presence pervade the historic building.', 1888, 'https://suitelifesanburg.com/haunted-places-in-st-augustine/'),

  ('lightner-museum', 'Lightner Museum', 'St. Augustine', '75 King Street', 'FL', 29.8905, -81.3131, 'museum', 'Originally the Hotel Alcazar, built by Henry Flagler in 1888 as a companion to the Hotel Ponce de Leon across the street. The building housed the world''s largest indoor swimming pool, now converted to a cafe and antique shops.', 'A little girl fell into the hotel pool and drowned during its years as a luxury resort. If visitors stand in the middle of the former pool area, close their eyes and concentrate, they can hear splashing water. A person is reportedly buried somewhere on the grounds. The connection to Flagler College via a 1902 bridge may allow spirits to travel between the two haunted buildings.', 1888, 'https://staugustinelandandseatours.com/ghosts-of-st-augustine/'),

  ('casablanca-inn', 'Casablanca Inn on the Bay', 'St. Augustine', '24 Avenida Menendez', 'FL', 29.8913, -81.3087, 'hotel', 'A Mediterranean Revival-style inn built in 1914, overlooking Matanzas Bay and the Castillo de San Marcos. During Prohibition, the inn''s owner allegedly signaled rum runners with a lantern to indicate when the coast was clear.', 'The ghost of the Prohibition-era owner still signals from the widow''s walk with her lantern, unaware that her bootlegging days ended decades ago. Staff members witness the light swinging late at night. Guests report cold spots, doors opening on their own, and the feeling of being watched. Some have seen a woman in period clothing walking the upper floors before vanishing.', 1914, 'https://ghostcitytours.com/st-augustine/haunted-st-augustine/casablanca-inn/'),

  ('ripley-believe-it-or-not', 'Ripley''s Believe It or Not! Museum', 'St. Augustine', '19 San Marco Avenue', 'FL', 29.8970, -81.3107, 'museum', 'Housed in Castle Warden, built in 1887 as a private residence and later converted to a hotel. The building witnessed unsolved murders and unexplained phenomena, earning its reputation as "the most haunted place on the Southeastern Seaboard."', 'Ripley''s Investigators of the Paranormal conduct 60-minute investigations of Castle Warden, documenting extensive paranormal activity. The building''s history of unsolved murders has left restless spirits behind. Visitors on investigations capture unexplained phenomena and encounter spirits from the castle''s dark past. Cold spots, shadow figures, and disembodied voices are regularly reported.', 1887, 'https://www.visitstaugustine.com/things-to-do/ghost-tours'),

  ('st-francis-inn', 'St. Francis Inn', 'St. Augustine', '279 St. George Street', 'FL', 29.8892, -81.3132, 'hotel', 'Florida''s oldest continuously operating inn, established in 1791 as a modest dwelling and expanded over centuries. The building has served as a private residence, boarding house, and bed and breakfast through Spanish, British, and American rule.', 'Lily, a young enslaved woman who fell in love with a soldier, died under mysterious circumstances and now haunts room 3A. Guests wake to find their belongings rearranged, feel someone sitting on the bed, and see her apparition in the mirror. She is a gentle spirit who seems to enjoy the company of visitors. The inn''s 230+ years of history have left multiple spirits in residence.', 1791, 'https://ghostcitytours.com/st-augustine/haunted-places/st-francis-inn/'),

  ('tolomato-cemetery', 'Tolomato Cemetery', 'St. Augustine', '14 Cordova Street', 'FL', 29.8965, -81.3110, 'cemetery', 'The oldest existing European-origin cemetery in Florida, dating to 1777 when it served as the burial ground for the Tolomato Indian Mission. Contains the graves of early Spanish settlers, Catholic priests, and victims of disease and war.', 'James, a young boy who died of yellow fever, roams the cemetery looking for playmates. Visitors report seeing child-sized shadows darting between tombstones. The ghost of Bishop Jean Pierre Augustin Verot, who established many Florida churches, has been seen near his elaborate tomb. Strange lights, cold spots, and the feeling of being watched pervade this ancient burial ground.', 1777, 'https://staugustineghosttours.com/tolomato-cemetery/');

