VALUES
  ('fort-east-martello', 'Fort East Martello Museum', 'Key West', '3501 South Roosevelt Boulevard', 'FL', 24.5472, -81.7553, 'museum', 'An 1862 Civil War-era brick fortress that now serves as a museum and the permanent home of Robert the Doll. The fort''s shadowy halls house 42 documented spirits and some of Key West''s most notoriously haunted artifacts.', 'Robert the Doll, created by the Steiff Company around 1904, moves on his own, changes facial expressions, and causes misfortune to those who disrespect him. Visitors have seen his chest move as if breathing and felt an unknown entity touching their knees. People who photograph Robert without permission report lost luggage, car accidents, and even being struck by lightning. The museum receives thousands of apology letters from terrified former visitors.', 1862, 'https://robertthedoll.org/visit/'),

  ('artist-house', 'Artist House', 'Key West', '534 Eaton Street', 'FL', 24.5587, -81.7989, 'mansion', 'A quintessential Key West Victorian house, originally the childhood home of Robert Eugene Otto, the boy who owned Robert the Doll. The house served as the artist''s residence until his death and is now a bed and breakfast.', 'Even though Robert the Doll moved to the museum decades ago, doors still open and close by themselves and lights flicker mysteriously. Guests see the apparition of a young woman on the stairs and standing at the foot of their beds - believed to be Anne, Robert Otto''s wife. Anne reportedly hated the doll and locked it in the attic, where neighbors saw it moving from window to window.', 1890, 'https://suitelifesanburg.com/key-west-haunted/'),

  ('captain-tonys-saloon', 'Captain Tony''s Saloon', 'Key West', '428 Greene Street', 'FL', 24.5597, -81.8032, 'restaurant', 'Originally built in 1851 as an icehouse and morgue, later becoming a wireless telegraph station, cigar factory, bordello, and speakeasy. Ernest Hemingway frequented the bar from 1933-1937 when it was Sloppy Joe''s.', 'The Lady in Blue was hanged from the building''s gallows tree after murdering her husband and two sons - her ghost in a blood-soaked blue dress haunts the premises. The hanging tree, which killed at least 75 pirates, still stands inside the bar. In the 1980s, renovations unearthed a dozen bodies beneath the floor, including a gravestone for a woman named Elvira. Patrons experience locked bathroom stalls with no one inside.', 1851, 'https://www.ghostsandgravestones.com/key-west/captain-tonys-saloon'),

  ('audubon-house-key-west', 'Audubon House & Tropical Gardens', 'Key West', '205 Whitehead Street', 'FL', 24.5593, -81.8022, 'museum', 'A 19th-century home originally owned by Captain John Geiger, a wealthy wrecker and harbor pilot. Named for naturalist John James Audubon, who visited Key West in 1832. The property has been certified as haunted by multiple paranormal societies.', 'Captain Geiger lost several children to yellow fever, and another died after falling from a tropical almond tree beside the house. An infant is buried in front of the home. Little Hannah haunts the children''s room, where toys move and her laughter echoes. Charles, the youngest Geiger child, tugs at visitors'' clothing. A tall man in a ruffled shirt and long jacket appears at the entry porch before vanishing.', 1846, 'https://southernmostghosts.com/most-haunted-places-in-key-west-6-audubon-house-and-gardens/'),

  ('la-concha-hotel', 'La Concha Hotel', 'Key West', '430 Duval Street', 'FL', 24.5570, -81.8022, 'hotel', 'Key West''s first luxurious hotel, built in 1926 with a scenic rooftop bar and decorative marble floors. The tallest building in Key West attracted famous guests including Ernest Hemingway and Tennessee Williams.', 'More than a dozen people have leaped from the roof over 95 years. In the 1980s, a busboy backing into an empty elevator shaft fell to his death - his ghost still wheels a cart toward the elevator before walking through the doors and vanishing. The elevator stops on the fifth floor by itself. A depressed spirit knocks wine glasses from guests'' hands. Objects fly across the Hemingway Suite and beds shake in the middle of the night.', 1926, 'https://ghostcitytours.com/key-west/haunted-key-west/la-concha-hotel/'),

  ('marreros-guest-mansion', 'Marrero''s Guest Mansion', 'Key West', '410 Fleming Street', 'FL', 24.5579, -81.8014, 'hotel', 'Built in 1889 by Francisco Marrero for his wife Enriquetta and their eight children. What the family didn''t know was that Francisco was already married to another woman in Cuba.', 'When Francisco died, his first wife arrived with lawyers and banished Enriquetta and her children from the mansion. Before leaving, Enriquetta vowed her spirit would always remain - and it has. Guests see her brushing her hair in mirrors and smell her lavender perfume. The children''s playroom door locks and unlocks by itself even after multiple replacements. Babies crying and children laughing echo through the 21+ only property.', 1889, 'https://www.hauntedrooms.com/florida/haunted-places/haunted-hotels/marreros-guest-mansion-key-west'),

  ('hard-rock-cafe-key-west', 'Hard Rock Cafe Key West', 'Key West', '313 Duval Street', 'FL', 24.5578, -81.8018, 'restaurant', 'Housed in an 1888 Victorian mansion originally built for Robert Curry, son of Florida''s first millionaire William Curry. The building later served as an Elk''s Lodge before becoming a restaurant.', 'Robert Curry suffered chronic illness his entire life and fell into deep depression after losing his father''s fortune. Though he died in New York, legends claim he hanged himself in the upstairs bathroom. His restless spirit has been reported since the Elk''s Lodge days. Shadow figures appear on the staircase, an unseen presence whistles and walks through the kitchen, and employees feel watched in the office.', 1888, 'https://suitelifesanburg.com/key-west-haunted/'),

  ('key-west-cemetery', 'Key West Cemetery', 'Key West', '701 Passover Lane', 'FL', 24.5555, -81.7952, 'cemetery', 'Established in 1847 after a hurricane washed away the original beachside cemetery, scattering coffins throughout the streets. The 19-acre cemetery contains approximately 100,000 burials, including many above-ground vaults due to the high water table.', 'The cemetery''s most famous epitaph reads "I Told You I Was Sick." Visitors report seeing apparitions of Cuban immigrants, sailors, and victims of the 1898 USS Maine explosion who are buried here. At night, shadows move between the elaborate tombs and mausoleums. The spirits of those whose coffins were scattered by the 1846 hurricane seem unable to rest. Cold spots occur even in the tropical heat.', 1847, 'https://www.hauntedplaces.org/key-west-fl/'),

  ('old-town-manor-key-west', 'Old Town Manor', 'Key West', '511 Eaton Street', 'FL', 24.5586, -81.7984, 'hotel', 'A former lodge now serving as a bed and breakfast inn. The beautiful old building was once home to Dr. William Warren and his wife Genevieve, who lived and worked in the historic property.', 'Dr. Warren and Genevieve never left their beloved home. Guests hear the doctor typing on his old school typewriter, and both apparitions have been seen throughout the property. Unexplained footsteps and electrical issues plague the inn. One woman was repeatedly tucked in by invisible hands while sleeping. Guests return to find belongings scattered, see presences sitting on their beds, and feel overwhelming sadness accompanied by wistful sighs.', 1880, 'https://southernmostghosts.com/the-most-haunted-hotels-in-key-west/');

