  ('don-cesar-hotel', 'The Don CeSar Hotel', 'St. Pete Beach', '3400 Gulf Boulevard', 'FL', 27.7254, -82.7385, 'hotel', 'A stunning pink Mediterranean-style resort built in the 1920s by Thomas Rowe as a tribute to his lost love, Lucinda. The "Pink Lady" served as a VA hospital during World War II and is now a luxury beach resort.', 'Thomas Rowe met Spanish opera star Lucinda in Spain, but her mother forbade their marriage. Heartbroken, he built the pink hotel inspired by the one where they fell in love. Staff and guests see Rowe in a white suit and Panama hat strolling with a beautiful woman with long black hair - Thomas and Lucinda together at last. Soldiers who died at the WWII hospital still haunt the grounds.', 1928, 'https://usghostadventures.com/haunted-places/don-cesar-hotel/'),

  ('cuban-club', 'The Cuban Club', 'Tampa', '2010 Avenida Republica de Cuba', 'FL', 27.9614, -82.4388, 'other', 'A magnificent social club built in 1917 for Tampa''s Cuban immigrant community, featuring a ballroom, theatre, bowling alley, and swimming pool. Now on the National Register of Historic Places and considered America''s most haunted building.', 'Over 300 spirits inhabit the Cuban Club. Rosalita was thrown from the third-floor balcony after rejecting a man''s advances - she now dances the waltz that never happened. An 8-year-old boy drowned in the basement swimming pool. Playwright Victorio took his life in the theatre after forgetting his lines on opening night. The elevator moves on its own, ghostly piano music plays, and drums echo through empty halls. TAPS investigated in 2009.', 1917, 'https://www.fox13news.com/news/the-cuban-club-is-one-of-the-oldest-ybor-building-and-one-of-the-most-haunted-in-the-u-s'),

  ('tampa-theatre', 'Tampa Theatre', 'Tampa', '711 North Franklin Street', 'FL', 27.9501, -82.4588, 'theater', 'A lavishly decorated atmospheric theatre opened in 1926, designed to make audiences feel they were watching films under a Mediterranean night sky. The 1,400-pipe Mighty Wurlitzer organ still accompanies silent films.', 'Foster "Fink" Finley, the theatre''s first projectionist, died of a heart attack in 1965 and never left. Staff smell his cigarette smoke hovering in the projection booth despite the smoking ban. Rosa Rio, the organist who played the Wurlitzer until her death at 107 in 2010, is heard playing after the public leaves. Guests in the back rows of the balcony smell phantom cigarettes.', 1926, 'https://patch.com/florida/southtampa/visit-these-sites-if-you-dare-tampas-most-haunted-places'),

  ('plant-hall', 'Plant Hall (University of Tampa)', 'Tampa', '401 West Kennedy Boulevard', 'FL', 27.9448, -82.4654, 'hotel', 'Originally the lavish Tampa Bay Hotel built by railroad tycoon Henry B. Plant in 1891. The Moorish Revival building hosted presidents and wealthy travelers before becoming part of the University of Tampa in 1933.', 'Henry Plant''s ghost rushes at anyone who acknowledges his presence before vanishing - faculty advise newcomers to avoid eye contact. The Brown Man has glowing red eyes and appears throughout the building. An opera singer who leaped from the ballroom roof after heartbreak still screams at night. A phantom couple dances eternally in the former ballroom, and servants from the hotel era haunt the science wing.', 1891, 'https://nightlyspirits.com/haunted-plant-hall-at-the-university-of-tampa/'),

  ('henry-plant-museum', 'Henry B. Plant Museum', 'Tampa', '401 West Kennedy Boulevard', 'FL', 27.9448, -82.4654, 'museum', 'Located in the south wing of the original Tampa Bay Hotel, the museum preserves the Gilded Age grandeur of Henry Plant''s vision. The collection includes original furnishings and artifacts from the hotel''s luxurious past.', 'The museum hosts "An Eerie Evening at the Tampa Bay Hotel" where guests experience the building''s haunted history. Henry Plant himself has been seen in the museum galleries, forever watching over his greatest achievement. Visitors report cold spots, unexplained sounds, and the sense of being observed by unseen eyes. The dark energy from the building''s history as a hospital permeates the space.', 1891, 'https://www.plantmuseum.com/discover/nora-s-blog/haunted-history-in-tampa-with-an-eerie-evening-at-en'),

  ('may-stringer-house', 'May-Stringer House', 'Brooksville', '601 Museum Court', 'FL', 28.5553, -82.3872, 'mansion', 'A four-story Victorian home built in 1856 by John May, featuring seven gables and fourteen rooms. Known as the most haunted house in Florida, with 11 documented ghosts. Added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1997.', 'John May died two years after moving in. His wife Marena died giving birth, and their three-year-old daughter Jessie Mae also died in the house. Shadow figures, orbs, and the sound of crying children fill the home. In the attic, Gary - nicknamed "Mr. Nasty" - is attached to a trunk and known for sarcastic, colorful language. Featured on Ghost Hunters and Kindred Spirits for its extraordinary activity.', 1856, 'https://www.tampabay.com/life-culture/history/2021/10/21/in-brooksville-may-stringer-house-owns-its-floridas-most-haunted-title/'),

  ('capitol-theatre', 'Capitol Theatre', 'Clearwater', '405 Cleveland Street', 'FL', 27.9658, -82.8006, 'theater', 'A historic 1921 movie palace that has been beautifully restored to its original glory. The Mediterranean Revival-style building has served as a community gathering place for over a century.', 'Staff and performers report seeing shadowy figures in the balcony during rehearsals and performances. The ghost of a former projectionist is said to linger in the booth, adjusting equipment when no one is there. Cold spots appear throughout the auditorium, and some performers feel an unseen presence watching from the wings. Doors open and close on their own in the backstage areas.', 1921, 'https://www.cltampa.com/arts-entertainment/culture/article/20982642/top-7-haunted-spots-in-tampa-bay-from-pinellas-to-hillsborough'),

  ('safety-harbor-spa', 'Safety Harbor Resort and Spa', 'Safety Harbor', '105 North Bayshore Drive', 'FL', 28.0069, -82.6931, 'hotel', 'Built over natural mineral springs that Native Americans considered sacred healing waters. The spa has operated since 1926, attracting visitors seeking the curative properties of the five natural springs.', 'The spirits of Native Americans who considered these springs sacred healing grounds still protect the waters. Guests report seeing figures in traditional dress near the springs, particularly at dawn and dusk. Some visitors feel hands pushing them gently toward the water, as if being guided to healing. The mineral springs are said to hold powerful spiritual energy that attracts both the living and the dead.', 1926, 'https://www.cltampa.com/arts-entertainment/culture/article/20982642/top-7-haunted-spots-in-tampa-bay-from-pinellas-to-hillsborough'),

  ('ybor-city-museum', 'Ybor City Museum State Park', 'Tampa', '1818 East 9th Avenue', 'FL', 27.9609, -82.4390, 'museum', 'A museum preserving the history of Tampa''s historic Latin Quarter, housed in the 1923 Ferlita Bakery building. The cigar industry once made Ybor City the "Cigar Capital of the World," employing thousands of immigrants.', 'The ghosts of cigar workers who spent their lives rolling tobacco in Ybor City factories still walk the streets. In the museum, visitors smell phantom cigar smoke and hear Spanish conversations in empty rooms. The spirit of a baker is said to remain in the former Ferlita Bakery building. At night, apparitions of workers in period clothing are seen walking toward the old factories that no longer exist.', 1923, 'https://tampabay-tours.com/');

